The bolt is mismatched.  The stock has the normal dents/dings you'd expect with a wartime stock.  The bore has some wear, but plenty of rifling left.  It's a two-groove barrel and it is clean and bright.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin 81-DL Tube Fed Bolt Action
location: Near Faribault - South of the Twin Cities -, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
Update:  Sale Pending.  

For sale is a Marlin 81 DL (Deluxe) .22 rifle.  

Known originally as the  “.22 Cal Bolt Action Repeater Model 81-DL”; this is a rare tube fed bolt action that can hold 25 short, 20 long, or 18 long rifle .22 rounds.  

The rifle features a 24” round tapered blued steel barrel with Ballard type rifling and a crowned muzzle.  

It also has an American walnut military-type finish and one piece buttstock.  

It has what I believe is an original Williams peep sight on the receiver which has both windage and elevation adjustments.  This rifle also features a ramp front sight.  

The wood on this rifle is immaculate as is the finish which I think to be all original.  

Additional sites:  

http://thefiringline.com/forums/showthread.php?t=499444

http://www.xdtalk.com/forums/bolt-guns-precision-rifles/230073-marlin-model-81-dl.html

http://www.marlinowners.com/forum/rimfires/79726-model-81-pre-war-factory-original-peep-sight.html

I’ve been digging on the internet (uh-oh) and based on that believe I have narrowed the age of the rifle down.  Somewhere after ~1952 Marlin switched to Microgroove barrels.  This is not stamped as having that barrel which makes me believe the rifle was built between 1941 – 1952.  It also appears to have the “beavertail stock” which was standard from 1941 – 1942.  That makes me think it was made from 1941 – 1942.  

I had it to the range last year and had no issues with it.  I filled it with .22 LR rounds and had a good day at the range.  I then brought it home, cleaned it, oiled it, and there it has sat.  These days I’m oriented toward .308’s and distance shooting so this is for sale.  

This was built in an era when quality mattered and things were meant to last and be handed down many generations.  It was also built at a time when craftsman knew the value of a solid rifle that wouldn’t fail.  When you hold this it feels like a real rifle and not a dainty piece of plastic that might get brittle in the cold.  

If you have questions, would like more pictures, or just want to comment on how you or someone you know had one as a kid drop me a line.  

In the meanwhile, Happy Trails and aim true.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Marlin Model 99M1 Carbine – Rare Find Fully Intact
location: Near Faribault - South of Twin Cities -, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale is a Marlin Model 99M1 Carbine.  These are not easy to find anymore.  They are a lot of fun each time they offer the opportunity for functionality and nostalgia to meet in an ignition of powder.  

This tube fed .22 was designed to look like the popular M1 Carbine on what is basically the proven frame of a Marlin Model 99.  

I believe this rifle was manufactured between 1964 – 1968; I am basing that on this model starting production in 1964 and it having no serial number – which was required after 1968.  

The rear sight on this rifle is intact.  These alone are highly sought after by Model 99 – M1 collectors.  

I did another inspection of the rifle and I think even the leather sling is an original.  

“Starting in 1964, Marlin produced a modified variant of their popular Model 99 rimfire rifle, stylized to look and feel like the WWII- M1 Carbine. They took the standard 22-inch barrel of the design and cut it down to 18, the same length as the M1. This also produced an overall length of 37-inches, within a bullet's length of the original. Since the Marlin was a .22LR and not a .30 carbine, the action and barrel were lighter, at 4.75-pounds. Forgoing the detachable box magazine of the M1, Marlin kept the under barrel tube mag but shortened it to hold just 10-rounds to keep the profile of the gun similar. A stock redesign and military style ramp sights completed the transformation.”  

Information was quoted, liberated, and hijacked from the following sites:  

http://www.marlinforum.com/forum/f17/marlin-house-brand-listing-353/

http://www.gunvaluesboard.com/how-old-is-a-marlin-model-99-mi-22cal-lr-3225032.html

http://www.marlinforum.com/The-Marlin-99-M1-Carbine.html

I have had this rifle to the range and had no issues with it.  It was cleaned, oiled and returned to storage until I brought it out to get pictures for this posting.  

You’ve read this much so I’m guessing you’re still interested, so go ahead and send me an email and buy it.  It might just be the most fun you can get for this much money and you don't want to have passed, these don't come around often.  


Happy Trails.

title: For Sale:  Daewoo DR-200 223 AR-15 / AK-47 Rifle 120rd Mag
postcontent:
This Daewoo DR-200 rifle came in from one of our local customers as a trade-in and is in excellent condition. Previous owner reported firing it many years ago, but has kept it in a safe until now. Other than a few light marks from safe storage, we can see no other defects on the rifle. 

Daewoo Precision Industries K2 assault rifle was developed by the, South Korean, Agency for Defense Development and manufactured by S&T Motiv (formerly Daewoo Precision Industries). It is currently the standard service rifle of the Republic of Korea Armed Forces. Shoulder-fired and gas-operated, the K2 is capable of firing both 5.56x45mm NATO and .223 Remington ammunition. The K2 supplanted the M16A1assault rifle for the Republic of Korea Armed Forces since its adoption in 1984. 

Comes with a Chinese Norinco 120rd AR-15 or Daewoo drum magazine chambered in .223 or 5.56mm. These were most likely made for the Daewoo series of rifles but will fit any AR-15 rifle. Made just like the standard AK-47 drum magazines, these are durable, easy to load, and can be kept loaded and unwound for many years. The C-Products or cheaper polymer double-snail drums require lubrication and constant maintenance for reliable operation – not these. They will run, and run, and run . . . round after round . . . and almost never fail to fire. These of course were imported well before the Clinton ban (1989 era) and so are “pre-ban” – never to be imported again due to the arms restrictions with China.

title: For Sale:  Daewoo DR-200 223 AR-15 / AK-47 Rifle 120rd Mag
postcontent:
This Daewoo DR-200 rifle came in from one of our local customers as a trade-in and is in excellent condition. Previous owner reported firing it many years ago, but has kept it in a safe until now. Other than a few light marks from safe storage, we can see no other defects on the rifle. 

Daewoo Precision Industries K2 assault rifle was developed by the, South Korean, Agency for Defense Development and manufactured by S&T Motiv (formerly Daewoo Precision Industries). It is currently the standard service rifle of the Republic of Korea Armed Forces. Shoulder-fired and gas-operated, the K2 is capable of firing both 5.56x45mm NATO and .223 Remington ammunition. The K2 supplanted the M16A1assault rifle for the Republic of Korea Armed Forces since its adoption in 1984. 

Comes with a Chinese Norinco 120rd AR-15 or Daewoo drum magazine chambered in .223 or 5.56mm. These were most likely made for the Daewoo series of rifles but will fit any AR-15 rifle. Made just like the standard AK-47 drum magazines, these are durable, easy to load, and can be kept loaded and unwound for many years. The C-Products or cheaper polymer double-snail drums require lubrication and constant maintenance for reliable operation – not these. They will run, and run, and run . . . round after round . . . and almost never fail to fire. These of course were imported well before the Clinton ban (1989 era) and so are “pre-ban” – never to be imported again due to the arms restrictions with China.

CZ 75 SP-01 TACTICAL 9mm 18RD 91152 with safety AVAILABLE AT DEGUNS.NET

The Tactical variant of the SP-01 utilizes an ambidextrous decocker in place of the manual safety on the standard SP-01.

The CZ 75 SP-01 is the first full size handgun (4.61” bbl) from CZ to feature the improved manufacturing technology and ergonomics of the NATO-approved CZ 75 Compact P-01 model. Featuring an integral 1913 accessory rail on the dust cover, rubber grip panels, and CZ’s corrosion resistant black polycoat finish, the SP-01 is the newest model to join the family of pistols based on the CZ 75 (SA/DA) platform. Borrowing from the improved grip geometry of the compact P-01, the SP-01 utilizes an extended beavertail to protect shooter’s strong hand as well as allowing for a deeper and more secure grip. The new grip geometry, checkering in key areas on the front and back straps, and redistribution of mass provided by the accessory rail noticeably decrease the perceived recoil from previous models and allows for more rapid target acquisition and transition.

The SP-01 was designed as a military and law enforcement duty sidearm. The new model is currently in use by security forces fighting the war on terrorism. Thanks to its exceptional accuracy and superior handling characteristics, the CZ 75 SP-01 has also found supporters in the field of sport and target shooting. Its list of users on the competition circuit include World Champions Adam Tyc and Angus Hobdell (1st and 3rd place respectively in 2005‘s IPSC championship, World Shoot XIV).
